Emergency Warning
 
Issued For: Wye River, Separation Creek
Fire Origin: Wye River, Separation Creek
Incident Name:
Issued: 26/12/15 2:22 AM
 
This is an Emergency Warning issued by Country Fire Authority for Wye River, Separation Creek.
 
There is a fast moving, out of control bushfire travelling in a southerly direction towards Wye River and Separartion Creek.
 
 
You are in danger, act now to protect yourself.
It is too late to leave. The safest option is to take shelter indoors immediately.
 
The relief centre is located at Apollo Bay Leisure Centre 34 Costin Street 
 
The next update is expected by 26/12/15 3:30 AM or as the situation changes.
 
For people affected by the Lorne bushfire in Victoria, register to let family and friends know you're OK. Visit redcross.org.au
 
Safety Information
When indoors:
  • Close all exterior doors, windows and vents and turn off cooling systems.
  • Shelter in a room that has a door and or a window to the outside - It is critical to keep an eye on what is happening with the fire.

If you cannot get indoors, other last resort options include:

  • A large open area like a ploughed paddock, football oval or sporting reserve.
  • A large body of water like a dam, lake, river, the ocean or inground pool.
  • Try to protect yourself from the fire's heat.

In the car:

  • Park behind a solid structure to block the fire's heat or pull over to a cleared area.
  • Try to position the car towards the approaching fire.
  • Put on your hazard lights and headlights.
  • Turn the engine off, close all windows and ensure that car air vents are closed.
  • Get down as low as possible below window level and cover up with a woolen blanket.

If you are travelling, do not enter the area, U-turn to safety.

If you are away from home, do not return.

For life or property threatening emergencies call 000

If you need medical advice for burns or smoke exposure call Nurse on Call on 1300 606 024

Stay Informed:

  • Via www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • Tune to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations or Sky News TV
  • Call the Victorian Bushfire Information Line (VBIL) on freecall 1800 240 667
  • Deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment can contact VBIL via the National Relay Service on 1800 555 677.
  • For help with English, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to telephone VBIL. If you know someone who cannot speak English, provide them with this number.
  • Download the FireReady App and follow Vic Emergency on Twitter (#VicFires) or Facebook.
  • Road Closures: check VicRoads Website.

The Bicentennial National Trail between Tom Groggin and Geehi, and the Murraygate Track are open.

All of Kosciuszko National Park is open.

Community Update

 
SCOTSBURN FINNS ROAD SCOTSBURN
ISSUED: 25/12/15 4:40 PM

This update is being issued by Country Fire Authority for the communities affected by the Scotsburn Finns Road fire.
 
Incident Information:
The Scotsburn - Finns Road fire is under control.  Crews are continuing to patrol the perimeter and extinguishing smouldering areas.  As such, smoke will be visible from nearby communities. 
 
The fire is approximately 4600 hectares in size.
 
There is currently no threat to communities but you should continue to stay informed and monitor conditions.
 
Smoke will be visible from nearby communities and roads.  Drivers should remain aware there are fire trucks and machinery still operating in the area, drive to current conditions and adhere to road signage.   
 
Towns impacted include Clarendon, Elaine, Grenville, Scotsburn.
 
Weather Conditions:
Forecast for Saturday 26 December  2015.  Central District
 
Cloudy. Very high (90%) chance of a thunderstorm in the morning and early afternoon. Winds northerly 25 to 35 km/h shifting south westerly before dawn. Overnight temperatures falling to between 12 and 15 with daytime temperatures about 20 degrees
Forecast for Sunday 27 December 2015.  Central District
 
Partly cloudy. Medium (50%) chance of showers near the coast, slight (20%)
chance elsewhere. Winds southerly 15 to 25 km/h. Overnight temperatures falling
to between 8 and 12 with daytime temperatures reaching between 18 and 22.
 
Community Meeting:
 
6:00 pm, Monday 28th December, 2016
Buninyong Town Hall
Learmonth Road, Buninyong
 
Relief & Respite Information:
 
RELIEF CENTRE
Buninyong Football and Netball Oval
Cnr Forest and Cornish Streets, Buninyong
 
Open 10am to noon, Saturday 26 December 2015 (Boxing Day)
Closed, Sunday 27 December 2015
Open 10am to 2pm, Monday 28 December 2015 (Boxing Day holiday)
 
Contact over the Christmas period for urgent issues when the relief centre is not open:
Moorabool Shire Council Recovery -  0400 886 453
City of Ballarat Recovery -  0447 109 877
Recovery Information Line - 1300 799 232
 
If you have been affected by the emergency please register with Red Cross online at www.redcross.org.au or call 1800 131 701.
 
FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE
Financial aid is available to eligible residents impacted by fire.  Payments include Emergency Relief Assistance and Emergency Re-establishment Payments.  To enquire about financial assistance visit the Buninyong Relief Centre or call your local council, or visit  http://www.vic.gov.au/news/disaster-assistance-for-the-victorian-bushfires-of-19-and-20-December.html
 
 
SCOTSBURN BUSHFIRE APPEAL
There has been an overwhelming and generous support from the community to aid those affected by the fire with immediate needs such as food, clothing, toys and Christmas presents.  Due to this response, no further goods are needed at this time.  If you wish to support the communities affected by the fire, please send you cash donations to:
 
Bendigo Bank
BSB: 633 000
Account Number: 156 382 715
 
VICROADS
88 Learmonth Road, Wendouree
 
VicRoads will fast track licence replacements of any community member affected by the fire.  Redundant vehicle registrations will be refunded with cash on the spot.
 
Information on updated road now open to all public, licence assistance or vehicle queries is available via 13 11 70 or the VicRoads website www.vicroads.vic.gov.au
 
SKIP BINS
21 skip bins have been distributed within the fire perimeter and are for household rubbish only. Collection dates are;
Saturday 26 December, 1:00 pm
Monday 28 December, 10:00 am
* Maps are available at the Relief Centre of their location
 
AUSTRALIA POST
Anyone in the bushfire affected areas can have their mail redirected for free for 12 months.  Ask you local Post Office.  Community members without a current residential address can have the redirection to a post office.  For further information, call Australia Post on 13 13 18 or ring any branch.
 
POWERCOR
POWERCOR advises residents in the affected area to be aware of fallen power lines.  If you need reconnection to your electricity supply please contact a registered electrician.  For further information, www.powercor.com.au
 
Safety Information & Emergency Contacts:
HAZARDOUS TREES
If individuals come across hazardous trees, contact 0419 887 065
 
INJURED ANIMALS
Following a bushfire, many surviving animals may be injured, disorientated or orphaned.  They may be looking for food, water or shelter. 
 
If you are able to safely take the animal into your care, carry in a secure box, or depending it the animal is smaller, a pillowcase.  Try to keep it calm by not making sudden or loud noises.
Call DELWP on 5335 0726.
 
If you are not able to safely capture the animal, take note of where you saw the animal, what species it was and what its behaviour was like, or if it was burned.  If you can safely mark where you saw it with what comes to hand, or the nearest road details, this is great. 
Call DELWP on 5335 0726.
 
Health & Wellbeing Information:
The Department of Health and Human Services offer a range or support services including personal, emotional, psychological and financial help.  For information go to www.recovery.vic.gov.au

  • Turn on your vehicle headlights and drive slowly; smoke will make it difficult to see.
  • This advice is current as of 26/12/15 1:30 AM Police are continuing to visit and advise residents.
  • After 26/12/15 1:30 AM it may be too late to leave, take shelter when the fire arrives - protect yourself from the fire's heat.
  • Last resort options include a Neighbourhood Safer Place, a stationary car in a cleared area, a ploughed paddock or reserve or body of water like a swimming pool or dam.
  • If you are away from home; do not return.
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you.
Incident Information:
  • This bushfire is currently creating spot-fires up to 1-2km ahead.
  • It is expected to travel toward Lorne later in the evening
  • A south west wind change is expected andmay cause the fire to head towards Lorne.
  • Victoria Police Community Evacuation Information: http://www.police.vic.gov.au/content.asp?Document_ID=39879.

Stay Informed:

For General Bushfire Information:
  • Victorian Bushfire Information Line (VBIL) on freecall 1800 240 667 or www.cfa.vic.gov.au.
 
Stay Informed: 
  • ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations or watching Sky News TV.
  • Deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment can contact VBIL via the National Relay Service on 1800 555 677.
  • For help with English, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to telephone VBIL. If you know someone who cannot speak English, provide them with this number.
  • Road closures: Check www.vicroads.vic.gov.au
  • Tourists: Stay away from the listed areas.
  • For life or property threatening emergencies: Call 000
  • Map: None

Advice
 
 
Issued For: Sunbury
Fire Origin: SUNBURY
Incident Name:  
Issued: 26/12/15 1:10 AM
 
This is a DOWNGRADED Advice message issued by Country Fire Authority for Sunbury.
Firefighters have stopped the spread of the grassfire in the SUNBURY area and fire activity has subsided.  The grassfire is now under control.
 
A wind change is expected around 2:00 AM, which may cause problems for the fire, so please continue to stay informed. The grassfire is under control.

You are no longer under any threat but should continue to monitor conditions and stay informed.

Racecourse Road is open for local residents only. Please continue to keep surrounding roads free for emergency services vehicles.

Smoke will be visible from nearby communities and roads.
The next update is expected by 26/12/15 11:00 AM or as the situation changes.
 
Safety Information:
  • If you have time, check your neighbours to see if they are monitoring conditions.
  • Continue to stay informed and monitor conditions.
  • Contact a family member or friend to tell them what you plan to do now.
  • If you are experiencing smoke exposure, seek medical advice or call Nurse on Call on 1300 606 024.

Stay Informed:

  • Via www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • Tune to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Call the Victorian Bushfire Information Line (VBIL) on freecall 1800 240 667.
  • Deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment can contact VBIL via the National Relay Service on 1800 555 677.
  • For help with English, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to telephone VBIL. If you know someone who cannot speak English, provide them with this number.
  • Download the FireReady App or follow Vic Emergency on Twitter (#VicFires) or Facebook.
  • Road closures: check VicRoads website.
